Pass TWINE_REPOSITORY_URL through.

issue.title: Have a skeleton.py file like in PyScaffold
issue.body:
## Describe your use-case
@sgbaird motivated that having a `skeleton.py` might be useful for his data science project setup. [[#642](https://github.com/pyscaffold/pyscaffold/issues/642)]

## Describe the solution you would like to see for your use-case
Just do not automatically activate the `--no-skeleton` extension in this extension.

comment.body:
Hi @sgbaird, thanks for your comments. It makes more sense, and is also more of a best practice, to have a `cli.py` within the actual package, i.e. within `src/pkg_name`. One could move as you suggested `train_model.py` to `cli.py` with the corresponding notes as in `skeleton.py`, e.g. like the `console_scripts` settings in `setup.cfg`. One could do this by default and additionally provide a `no-cli` command-line-option if some users don't want it.

The script you provided above is a bit complicated and outdated for an example, to be honest. For instance:
```python
@click.option("-v", "--verbose", "log_level", flag_value=logging.INFO)
@click.option("-vv", "--very-verbose", "log_level", flag_value=logging.DEBUG)
def main(cfg_path: Path, log_level: int):
```
allows you to have the log level directed in `log_level` so you can do then just: 
```python
  logging.basicConfig(
      stream=sys.stdout,
      level=log_level,
      datefmt="%Y-%m-%d %H:%M",
      format="%(asctime)s - %(name)s - %(levelname)s - %(message)s",
  )
```
and save all the `if`s in the example code. Also consider using Python's `pathlib` library instead of `os.path`. This also makes the code more robust and even simpler. 

I even wonder if one should nowadays even recommend [typer](https://typer.tiangolo.com/) instead of `click` as it uses type-hinting and makes writing a CLI even simpler than click. 

Would you want to work on a PR? I can provide coaching if you want to but have no time myself to implement it right now.

issue.title: Have a skeleton.py file like in PyScaffold
issue.body:
## Describe your use-case
@sgbaird motivated that having a `skeleton.py` might be useful for his data science project setup. [[#642](https://github.com/pyscaffold/pyscaffold/issues/642)]

## Describe the solution you would like to see for your use-case
Just do not automatically activate the `--no-skeleton` extension in this extension.

comment.body:
Hi @sgbaird, thanks for your comments. It makes more sense, and is also more of a best practice, to have a `cli.py` within the actual package, i.e. within `src/pkg_name`. One could move as you suggested `train_model.py` to `cli.py` with the corresponding notes as in `skeleton.py`, e.g. like the `console_scripts` settings in `setup.cfg`. One could do this by default and additionally provide a `no-cli` command-line-option if some users don't want it.

The script you provided above is a bit complicated and outdated for an example, to be honest. For instance:
```python
@click.option("-v", "--verbose", "log_level", flag_value=logging.INFO)
@click.option("-vv", "--very-verbose", "log_level", flag_value=logging.DEBUG)
def main(cfg_path: Path, log_level: int):
```
allows you to have the log level directed in `log_level` so you can do then just: 
```python
  logging.basicConfig(
      stream=sys.stdout,
      level=log_level,
      datefmt="%Y-%m-%d %H:%M",
      format="%(asctime)s - %(name)s - %(levelname)s - %(message)s",
  )
```
and save all the `if`s in the example code. Also consider using Python's `pathlib` library instead of `os.path`. This also makes the code more robust and even simpler. 

I even wonder if one should nowadays even recommend [typer](https://typer.tiangolo.com/) instead of `click` as it uses type-hinting and makes writing a CLI even simpler than click. 

Would you want to work on a PR? I can provide coaching if you want to but have no time myself to implement it right now.

notion_orm = notional.connect(auth=AUTH_TOKEN)

issue.body:
## Describe your use-case
@sgbaird motivated that having a `skeleton.py` might be useful for his data science project setup. [[#642](https://github.com/pyscaffold/pyscaffold/issues/642)]

## Describe the solution you would like to see for your use-case

comment.body:
Hi @sgbaird, thanks for your comments. It makes more sense, and is also more of a best practice, to have a `cli.py` within the actual package, i.e. within `src/pkg_name`. One could move as you suggested `train_model.py` to `cli.py` with the corresponding notes as in `skeleton.py`, e.g. like the `console_scripts` settings in `setup.cfg`. One could do this by default and additionally provide a `no-cli` command-line-option if some users don't want it.

The script you provided above is a bit complicated and outdated for an example, to be honest. For instance:
```python
@click.option("-v", "--verbose", "log_level", flag_value=logging.INFO)
@click.option("-vv", "--very-verbose", "log_level", flag_value=logging.DEBUG)
def main(cfg_path: Path, log_level: int):
```
allows you to have the log level directed in `log_level` so you can do then just: 
```python
  logging.basicConfig(
      stream=sys.stdout,
      level=log_level,
      datefmt="%Y-%m-%d %H:%M",
      format="%(asctime)s - %(name)s - %(levelname)s - %(message)s",
  )
```
and save all the `if`s in the example code. Also consider using Python's `pathlib` library instead of `os.path`. This also makes the code more robust and even simpler. 

I even wonder if one should nowadays even recommend [typer](https://typer.tiangolo.com/) instead of `click` as it uses type-hinting and makes writing a CLI even simpler than click. 

Would you want to work on a PR? I can provide coaching if you want to but have no time myself to implement it right now.
